<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40033b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40033b">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40033b"> 33(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">H</font> paints <font face="wake">A</font> ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;What the animist worships and seeks by all means to influence and conciliate is,&rdquo; says Sir Herbert Risley, &ldquo;the shifting and shadowy company of unknown powers or influences making for evil rather than good which reside in the primeval forest, in the crumbling hills, in the rushing river, in the spreading trees; which give its spring to the tiger, its venom to the snake; which generate jungle fever and walk abroad in the terrible guise of cholera, smallpox, and murrain. Closer than this he does not seek to define the object to which he offers his victim, or whose symbol he daubs with vermilion at the appointed season. <small> Rev W.S. Hunt, <a name="WSHI1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WSHI1"><cite title="source">India's Outcastes: A New Era</cite></a> (1924) 44</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
